abstract = {Cryptocurrencies exhibit high price volatility and a large degree of speculative activity relative to their usage as a means of payment. I present a model to explain these two facts. A cryptocurrency di ers from other assets due to two distinctive features: a price endogenously determined by the extent of its usage as money, and a structure that limits settlement capacity. A cryptocurrency payment is not nal until it is recorded on a ledger, known as a blockchain. Limited blockchain space means that there is competition between speculative and monetary usage. A user can purchase priority by o ering fees to any miner that adds her payment to the blockchain. Speculative pressure can drive these fees up and crowd out monetary uses. This crowding out undermines the ability of a cryptocurrency to serve as a medium of payment, reducing its value and thus its price. A lower price raises the information content of the trade order ow, making the price more volatile. This is the rst paper to endogenise both the nancial market for cryptocurrency, and the fee-based market for blockchain space. I show that prices of cryptocurrencies are inherently more volatile than those of other assets and, more profoundly, that price formation may work fundamentally di erently than for traditional assets. In particular, the demand curve can be locally upward-sloping, because the act of speculation reduces the value of the cryptocurrency.},
